29 SECTION 2, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
30 JULY 1, 2027]: Sec. 60. (a) As used in this section, "adequate welding
31 standards" means specifications, guidelines, tests, and other methods
32 used to ensure that all structural steel welds meet, at minimum, the
33 codes and standards for such welds established in the welding code and
34 under rules adopted by the fire prevention and building safety
35 commission under IC 22-13-2-2. department of homeland security.
36 (b) As used in this section, "certified welding inspector" means a
37 person who has been certified by the American Welding Society to
38 inspect structural steel welding projects and conduct welder
39 qualification tests.
40 (c) As used in this section, "structural steel welding" means
41 structural welds, weld repair, the structural system, and the welding of
42 all primary steel members of a structure in accordance with the welding
EH 1003—LS 6756/DI 92

40
1 code. The term does not include welding that is required by the
2 American Society of Mechanical Engineers to have its own
3 certification.
4 (d) As used in this section, "welding code" refers to the American
5 Welding Society structural steel welding code D1.1, as in effect on July
6 1, 2023.
7 (e) A contractor whose workers are welding the structural steel on
8 a project shall ensure that all of the following occur:
9 (1) The workers performing the structural steel welding have been
10 tested by, and hold a valid certification from, a facility that, or an
11 individual who, has been accredited by the American Welding
12 Society to test and certify welders and welding inspectors.
13 (2) All structural steel welds performed for the project meet
14 adequate welding standards and follow the project's special
15 provisions.
16 (3) All structural steel welding inspections listed in the project's
17 special provisions are completed by a certified welding inspector.
18 (f) If the department reasonably suspects a contractor has violated
19 this section, the department shall require the contractor to remedy the
20 violation not later than thirty (30) days after the department notifies the
21 contractor of the violation. The notification to the contractor must be
22 signed by the commissioner and sent by a method that enables the
23 department to verify receipt of the notice by the contractor. During the
24 thirty (30) day period, the contractor may continue to work on the
25 project. If the contractor fails to remedy the violation within the thirty
26 (30) day period, the department shall find the contractor not
27 responsible and determine the length of time the contractor is
28 considered not responsible by the department.
29 (g) In making the determination of the length of time a contractor is
30 not responsible under subsection (f), the department shall consider the
31 severity of the violation. The period during which a contractor is
32 considered not responsible:
33 (1) may not exceed forty-eight (48) months; and
34 (2) begins on the date of substantial completion of the project.
35 (h) A finding by the department under subsection (f) that a
36 contractor is not responsible may not be used by another state agency
37 or a political subdivision in making a determination as to whether the
38 contractor is responsible for purposes of that state agency's or political
39 subdivision's award of a public works contract to that contractor.
