4 SECTION 66. IC 10-14-3-9, AS AMENDED BY P.L.85-2015,
5 SECTION 2, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
6 JULY 1, 2027]: Sec. 9. (a) The agency shall prepare and maintain a
7 current state emergency operations plan. The plan may provide for the
8 following:
9 (1) Prevention and minimization of injury and damage caused by
10 disaster.
11 (2) Prompt and effective response to disaster.
12 (3) Emergency relief.
13 (4) Identification of areas particularly vulnerable to disaster.
14 (5) Recommendations for:
15 (A) zoning;
16 (B) building;
17 (C) other land use controls;
18 (D) safety measures for securing mobile homes or other
19 nonpermanent or semipermanent structures; and
20 (E) other preventive and preparedness measures designed to
21 eliminate or reduce disaster or its impact;
22 that must be disseminated to both the fire prevention and building
23 safety commission and local authorities.
24 (6) Assistance to local officials in designing local emergency
25 action plans.
26 (7) Authorization and procedures for the erection or other
27 construction of temporary works designed to protect against or
28 mitigate danger, damage, or loss from flood, conflagration, or
29 other disaster.
30 (8) Preparation and distribution to the appropriate state and local
31 officials of state catalogs of federal, state, and private assistance
32 programs.
33 (9) Organization of manpower and chains of command.
34 (10) Coordination of federal, state, and local disaster activities.
35 (11) Coordination of the state disaster plan with the disaster plans
36 of the federal government.
37 (12) Other necessary matters.
38 (b) The agency shall take an integral part in the development and
39 revision of local and interjurisdictional disaster plans prepared under
40 section 17 of this chapter. The agency shall employ or otherwise secure
41 the services of professional and technical personnel capable of
42 providing expert assistance to political subdivisions, a political
EH 1003—LS 6756/DI 92

46
1 subdivision's disaster agencies, and interjurisdictional planning and
2 disaster agencies. These personnel:
3 (1) shall consult with subdivisions and government agencies on
4 a regularly scheduled basis;
5 (2) shall make field examinations of the areas, circumstances, and
6 conditions to which particular local and interjurisdictional
7 disaster plans are intended to apply; and
8 (3) may suggest revisions.
9 (c) In preparing and revising the state disaster plan, the agency shall
10 seek the advice and assistance of local government, business, labor,
11 industry, agriculture, civic and volunteer organizations, and community
12 leaders. In advising local and interjurisdictional agencies, the agency
13 shall encourage local and interjurisdictional agencies to seek advice
14 from the sources specified in this subsection.
15 (d) The state disaster plan or any part of the plan may be
16 incorporated in rules of the agency or by executive orders.
17 (e) The agency shall do the following:
18 (1) Determine requirements of the state and political subdivisions
19 for food, clothing, and other necessities in the event of an
20 emergency.
21 (2) Procure and pre-position supplies, medicines, materials, and
22 equipment.
23 (3) Adopt standards and requirements for local and
24 interjurisdictional disaster plans.
25 (4) Provide for mobile support units.
26 (5) Assist political subdivisions, political subdivisions' disaster
27 agencies, and interjurisdictional disaster agencies to establish and
28 operate training programs and public information programs.
29 (6) Make surveys of industries, resources, and facilities in
30 Indiana, both public and private, necessary to carry out this
31 chapter.
32 (7) Plan and make arrangements for the availability and use of
33 any private facilities, services, and property, and if necessary and
34 if the private facilities, services, or property is used, provide for
35 payment for the use under agreed upon terms and conditions.
36 (8) Establish a register of persons with types of training and skills
37 important in emergency prevention, preparedness, response, and
38 recovery.
39 (9) Establish a register of mobile and construction equipment and
40 temporary housing available for use in a disaster emergency.
41 (10) Prepare, for issuance by the governor, executive orders,
42 proclamations, and regulations necessary or appropriate in coping
EH 1003—LS 6756/DI 92

47
1 with disaster.
2 (11) Cooperate with the federal government and any public or
3 private agency or entity in achieving any purpose of this chapter
4 and in implementing programs for disaster prevention,
5 preparation, response, and recovery.
6 (12) Do other things necessary, incidental, or appropriate to
7 implement this chapter.
8 (f) The agency shall ascertain the rapid and efficient
9 communications that exist in times of disaster emergencies. The agency
10 shall consider the desirability of supplementing these communications
11 resources or of integrating these resources into a comprehensive
12 intrastate or state-federal telecommunications or other communications
13 system or network. In studying the character and feasibility of any
