1 exposure to the hazard dealt with by the standard for the period of his
2 working life. Development of standards shall be based upon research,
3 demonstrations, experiments, and such other information as may be
4 appropriate. In addition to the attainment of the highest degree of
5 health and safety protection for the employee, other considerations
6 shall be the latest available scientific data in the field, the feasibility of
7 the standards, and experience gained under this and other health and
8 safety laws. Whenever practicable, the standard promulgated shall be
9 expressed in terms of objective criteria and of the performance desired.
10 (c) The commission, board, in promulgating standards, shall adopt
11 rules requiring employers to maintain accurate records of employee
12 exposures to potentially toxic material or harmful physical agents
13 which are required to be monitored or measured under the standards.
14 These rules shall provide employees or their representatives with an
15 opportunity to observe monitoring or measuring and to have access to
16 the records thereof. These rules shall also make appropriate provisions
17 for each employee to have access to such records as will indicate his
18 own exposure to toxic materials or harmful physical agents. Under
19 these rules, each employer shall notify any employee who is being
20 consistently exposed to toxic materials or harmful physical agents in
21 concentrations or at levels which exceed those prescribed by an
22 occupational safety and health standard and shall inform any employee
23 who is being thus exposed of the corrective action being taken.
