31 SECTION 261. IC 22-8-1.1-19.1 IS AMENDED TO READ AS
32 FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2027]: Sec. 19.1. Temporary
33 Variances. Any employer may apply to the commission board for a
34 temporary order granting a variance from a standard or any provision
35 thereof promulgated under this chapter. Such temporary order shall be
36 granted only if the employer establishes that he is unable to comply
37 with a standard by its effective date because of unavailability of
38 professional or technical personnel or of materials and equipment
39 needed to come into compliance with the standard or because necessary
40 construction or alteration of facilities cannot be completed by the
41 effective date; that he is taking all available steps to safeguard his
42 employees against the hazards covered by the standard; and that he has
EH 1003—LS 6756/DI 92

139
1 an effective program for coming into compliance with a standard as
2 quickly as practicable. Any temporary order issued under this section
3 shall prescribe the practices, means, methods, operations and processes
4 which the employer must adopt and use while the order is in effect and
5 state in detail his program for coming into compliance with the
6 standard. Such a temporary order may be granted only after notice to
7 employees and an opportunity for a hearing. Said notice shall be given
8 to the authorized representative of the employees and be posted at or
9 near the location for which the variance is sought. No order for a
10 temporary variance may be in effect for longer than the period needed
11 by the employer to achieve compliance with the standard or one (1)
12 year, whichever is shorter, except that such an order may be renewed
13 not more than twice, so long as the requirements of this paragraph are
14 met and if an application for renewal is filed at least ninety (90) days
15 prior to the expiration date of the order.
16 SECTION 262. IC 22-8-1.1-20.1 IS AMENDED TO READ AS
17 FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2027]: Sec. 20.1. Any affected
18 employer may apply to the commission board for a permanent variance
19 from a standard promulgated under this chapter. Affected employees
20 shall be given notice of each such application by posting it at or near
21 the location for which the variance is sought, and an opportunity to
22 participate in a hearing. The commission board shall issue such rule
23 or order if it determines, after a hearing, including an inspection, if
24 appropriate, that the proponent of the variance has demonstrated by a
25 preponderance of the evidence that the conditions, practices, means,
26 methods, operations, or processes used or proposed to be used by the
27 employer will provide employment and places of employment to his
28 employees which are as safe and healthful as those which would
29 prevail if he complied with the standard. The rule or order so issued
30 shall prescribe the conditions the employer must maintain, and the
31 practices, means, methods, operations, and processes which he must
32 adopt and utilize to the extent they differ from the standard in question.
33 Such a rule or order may be modified or revoked upon application by
34 an employer, employees, the commissioner of labor, or the commission
35 board on its own motion, in the manner prescribed for its issuance
36 under this section at any time after six (6) months from its issuance,
37 provided that the moving party gives thirty (30) days notice to the other
38 parties, and a hearing is held at the request of any of the parties.
